For a while, it felt like the Warriors were something completely novel: a dominant sports team with a refreshing lack of ego or internal conflict. This was back in, say, 2015, during their first title run. Sure, Draymond Green and Steve Kerr would get into it from time to time, but most spectators were largely impressed with the way they seemed to play with such joy.

In Ethan Strauss's new book "Victory Machine: The Making and Unmaking of the Warriors Dynasty," it becomes clear that the Warriors were never as harmonious as it seemed... READ MORE

